<DOC><DOCNO>  ZF108-218-531  </DOCNO><DOCID>08 218 531.andO;</DOCID><JOURNAL>IBM Systems Journal  Dec 1989 v28 n4 p600(13).andM;</JOURNAL><TITLE>An Arabic morphological system. (development of software in Arabiclanguage) (technical)</TITLE><AUTHOR>El-Sadany, Tarek A.; Hashish, Mohamed A.andM;</AUTHOR><TEXT><ABSTRACT>Nowadays, computers are used in every field in the Arab countriesof the middle east.andP;  Software systems developed for the Europeanlanguages are not convenient for the use of Arabic because of thenature of the language and its writing system.andP;  Problems arisewhen trying to use existing software systems, such asspell-checkers and business and office systems, with the Arabiclanguage.andP;  These problems are attributable to the fact that thedifference between Arabic and the European languages exist notonly in character shapes and direction of writing, but also inlanguage structure.andP;  In order to successfully use Arabic insoftware systems, we must, then, analyze the Arabic language wordstructure - that is, carry out a morphological analysis.andP;  Most ofthe written Arabic texts are non-vowelized, which may lead toambiguity in meaning or mispronunciation.andP;  Moreover, vowelizationcannot be avoided in many applications, such as speech synthesisby machines and educational books for children.andP;  A two-way Arabicmorphological system (analysis/generation) capable of dealing withvowelized, semi-vowelized, and nonvowelized Arabic words wasdeveloped at the IBM Cairo Scientific Center.andP;  The system also hasthe ability to vowelize nonvowelized words.andP;  This system consistsof three separate modules: computational lexicon, Arabic grammarmodel module, and analyzer/generator module.andP;  The grammar modulecontains, among others, morphophonemic and morphographemic rulesformulated using the conventional generative grammar.andP;  Moreover,the developed system covers all of the Arabic language.andO;(Reprinted by permission of the publisher.)andM;</ABSTRACT></TEXT><DESCRIPT>Topic:     Language TranslationNon-Roman AlphabetsResearch and DevelopmentSpelling CheckersSoftware DesignLinguisticsForeign LanguagesWritingArabic language.andM;</DESCRIPT></DOC>